\begin{align*}x &= \rho \sin \phi \cos \theta \\ y &= \rho \sin \phi \sin \theta \\ z &= \rho \cos \phi\end{align*}
In this case, we have $\rho = 2$, $\theta = \pi$, and $\phi = \frac{\pi}{4}$. Substituting these values into the formulas, we get:
\begin{align*}x &= 2\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right)\cos(\pi) = -\sqrt{2} \\ y &= 2\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right)\sin(\pi) = 0 \\ z &= 2\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) = \sqrt{2}\end{align*}
